cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software in research, please cite it using the metadata in this file, and consider acknowledging the upstream tools (GSD and research-unit-tests) it builds on."
type: software
title: "gsd-econ: A spec-driven workflow for empirical economics research"
abstract: >-
  gsd-econ is an overlay for the GSD (get-shit-done) framework that adapts its
  spec-driven development primitives to the structure of an empirical economics
  paper. It integrates the research-unit-tests taxonomy as the verification
  layer at every phase gate, adds methodology-aware commands and subagents
  (identification-checker, econometrician, replication-verifier, polish-pass,
  referee-sim with parallel deliberation), and enforces an audit trail from
  research question through submission. Designed for both new papers and
  mid-project adoption.
authors:
  - family-names: Michuda
    given-names: Aleksandr
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6855-5107"
    affiliation: "Swarthmore College"

repository-code: "https://github.com/amichuda/gsd-econ"
license: MIT
keywords:
  - empirical economics
  - causal inference
  - reproducible research
  - peer review automation
  - llm agents
  - spec-driven development
  - econometrics
  - replication

# Update these whenever you tag a release.
version: 0.3.0
date-released: "2026-05-12"

# Acknowledgments to upstream projects this work builds on. These are not
# co-authors — they're prior art / dependencies — so they go in `references`,
# not `authors`.
references:
  - type: software
    title: "get-shit-done (GSD): a context-engineering and orchestration framework for AI coding agents"
    authors:
      - name: "TÂCHES"
    repository-code: "https://github.com/gsd-build/get-shit-done"
    license: MIT
    notes: "gsd-econ is built as an overlay on top of GSD's primitives (discuss/plan/execute/verify loop, multi-agent orchestration, atomic commits)."

  - type: software
    title: "research-unit-tests: declarative quality checks for empirical research"
    authors:
      - name: "rdahis"
    repository-code: "https://github.com/rdahis/research-unit-tests"
    license: MIT
    notes: "research-unit-tests provides the test taxonomy (methodology, scope, severity, clarity tags) that gsd-econ uses as its verification grammar at every phase gate."

  - type: software
    title: "HeavySkill: Heavy Thinking as the Inner Skill in Agentic Harness"
    authors:
      - family-names: Wang
        given-names: Jianing
      - family-names: Guo
        given-names: Linsen
      - family-names: Chen
        given-names: Zhengyu
    repository-code: "https://github.com/wjn1996/HeavySkill"
    license: Apache-2.0
    notes: >-
      The architectural pattern in gsd-econ's --heavy mode of /gsd-referee-sim
      (K parallel light-tier agents synthesized by a heavy-tier deliberator)
      is conceptually inspired by HeavySkill. The integration with adversarial
      peer review is original. Full author list is available in the HeavySkill
      repository's README.

  - type: article
    title: "Hallucinations Undermine Trust; Metacognition is a Way Forward"
    authors:
      - family-names: Yona
        given-names: Gal
      - family-names: Geva
        given-names: Mor
      - family-names: Matias
        given-names: Yossi
    year: 2026
    identifiers:
      - type: other
        value: "arXiv:2605.01428"
        description: "arXiv preprint"
    url: "https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.01428"
    notes: >-
      The framing of rules/uncertainty-honesty.md — hallucinations as
      confident errors, the known/partial/unknown distinction, and uncertainty
      as a control signal for tool use — draws on this position paper.
